.so fork.tmac
.SS MACRO cli_prototype
.PP
Use the
.B cli_prototype
macro to style and format the arguments of a prototype for a command
line interface program.
This macro should be used immediately following the command name,
the length of which is used to establish an indent length to format
the arguments.
.\"
.PP
.gp_cli_prototype
.\"
Arguments to the
.B cli_prototype
macro use prefixes to indicate the desired style:
.TS
tab(|);
l l.
\fB@\fPvalue|user-supplied value (in italics)
\fB?\fPargument|optional argument (enclosed in square brackets)
\fB!\fP-a|verbatim argument (in bold)
\fB!\fP-b\fB:\fPvalue|verbatim option in bold, \fBvalue\fP in italic
.TE
.PP
Note that the
.B ?
prefix can go in front of any argument to enclose it in brackets.
.\"
.PP
For example, the following groff code:
.IP
.EX
\&.B command
\&.cli_prototype @required_argument \\
       !required_verbatim    \\
       !-r:required_option   \\
       ?@optional_argument   \\
       ?!-o:option           \\
       ?!--option:value      \\
       ?!-abcd ?!-v ?!--help
.EE
.PP
will generate this prototype:
.IP
.B command
.cli_prototype @required_argument \
       !required_verbatim    \
       !-r:required_option   \
       ?@optional_argument   \
       ?!-o:option           \
       ?!--option:value      \
       ?!-abcd ?!-v ?!--help
